# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The given code is an implementation of a method named lengthOfLastWord in a class named Solution. This method takes a string s as input and returns the length of the last word in the string.

Here's a step-by-step explanation of how the code works:

The input string s is trimmed using the trim() method. This removes any leading or trailing whitespace from the string.

The variable op is initialized to 0. This variable will store the length of the last word.

A for loop is used to iterate over the characters of the string s starting from the end (i.e., from s.length()-1 to 0).

Inside the loop, it checks if the current character is a space (' '). If it is, it means that the last word has ended, so the loop is exited using the break statement.

If the current character is not a space, the op variable is incremented by 1, indicating that another character has been encountered in the last word.

Finally, the method returns the value of op, which represents the length of the last word in the input string.

The code assumes that the input string contains words separated by a single space and there are no leading or trailing spaces within the last word.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The approach used in the given code is quite straightforward and intuitive. Here's a breakdown of the approach:

The first step is to remove any leading or trailing whitespace from the input string. This is done using the trim() method. This ensures that any spaces before or after the last word are ignored.

After trimming the string, the variable op is initialized to 0. This variable will store the length of the last word.

The for loop iterates over the characters of the string starting from the end (i.e., from s.length()-1 to 0). This is done to find the last word in the string.

Inside the loop, it checks if the current character is a space (' '). If it is, it means that the last word has ended. Therefore, the loop is exited using the break statement.

If the current character is not a space, it means that another character is a part of the last word. In that case, the op variable is incremented by 1.

Once the loop finishes, the value of op represents the length of the last word in the input string.

The overall approach is to trim the string, then start from the end and iterate backwards until a space is encountered, counting the characters in the last word. The loop breaks as soon as a space is found, assuming there are no trailing spaces within the last word. The final count of characters in the last word is returned as the result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(n)
