The easist way may be iterate from the end of the string, can we do that with a different way?
**Of course !**


### C# Examples  (Java and Python version please visit my blog)
**1. Iteration**
```
public class Solution {
    public int LengthOfLastWord(string s) {

        int cnt = 0;

        for(int i = s.Length-1;i>=0;i--)
        {
            if(Char.IsWhiteSpace(s[i]))
            {
                if(cnt>0)
                {
                    return cnt;    
                }
                continue;
            }

            cnt+=1;
        }
        return cnt;
    }
}
```

**2. Split + Trim**
```
public class Solution {
    public int LengthOfLastWord(string s) {
        s = s.TrimEnd();                 //or you can use Trim()
        string[] tmp = s.Split(' ');
        return tmp[tmp.Length-1].Length; 
    }
}
```
